ðŸ”¹ What is enum4linux?

    enum4linux is a Perl script that automates enumeration of Windows and Samba (SMB) services. It wraps common Samba utilities (like smbclient, rpcclient, net, nmblookup) to extract information such as shares, users, groups, password policy, OS details and more from SMB hosts.

ðŸ”¹ Why use enum4linux?

    -Fast SMB reconnaissance: collects a lot of useful info (shares, user lists, domain/group membership, password policies) with a single tool â€” great for pentests and network recon.


    -Wrapper for Samba tools: it automates many manual Samba commands so you donâ€™t have to run each tool separately.


    -Good first step: helps identify attack surface (exposed shares, weak configs) before using exploitation tools or manual follow-up.

ðŸ”¹ How to install (Kali)

    Kali usually ships enum4linux in its repos. Install / update and confirm dependencies (samba tools):

    sudo apt update
    sudo apt install enum4linux smbclient smbclient samba-common-bin
    sudo apt install enum4linux-ng

ðŸ”¹ Typical usage & common flags

Basic syntax:

    enum4linux [options] <target>
    perl enum4linux.pl [options] <target>

Common options (classic enum4linux variants and equivalents):

    1. -a : all the common checks (aggressive / comprehensive enumeration).

    2. -U : enumerate users.

    3. -S : enumerate shares.

    4. -G : enumerate groups.

    5. -P : password policy.

    6. -o <file> : output to file (varies by fork).

    7.-v : verbose/debug output.

Example commands

1.  Quick overview (all checks)

        enum4linux -a 10.10.10.5

2.  Enumerate shares only

        enum4linux -S 10.10.10.5

3.  Get users and password policy

        enum4linux -U -P 10.10.10.5

4.  Using the new python/ng tool (JSON output option)

        enum4linux-ng -t 10.10.10.5 --json-report report.json

5.  Run against multiple hosts (simple loop)

    for ip in $(cat targets.txt); do
     echo "== $ip =="
     enum4linux -a $ip | tee results/$ip.txt
    done
